review_comments:
['`hasToolConfirmation` is being set/reset by this batched confirmation part independently of the existing per-tool confirmation subparts. Because context keys aren’t ref-counted, when the original `ToolConfirmationSubPart` gets disposed on the first tool’s state transition it will reset the key to false/undefined even while the batch UI is still visible, breaking keybindings/"pending tool call" UI. Consider centralizing ownership of `ChatContextKeys.Editing.hasToolConfirmation` (e.g. set it based on whether any confirmation UI is currently mounted), or introduce a small ref-count helper so multiple confirmation widgets can coexist safely.

This issue also appears in the following locations of the same file:
- line 112
- line 254', 'On batch empty, this callback clears the reference but doesn’t remove or dispose the `ChatBatchedToolConfirmationPart` instance (it remains registered on this part) nor remove its `domNode` from the DOM. That can keep a hidden element/MutationObserver alive for the lifetime of the tool part. Consider disposing the batched confirmation part and removing its DOM node when it empties, and only then clear the reference.
```suggestion
		// When the batch empties, dispose and remove the batched part, then show this tool part again
		this._register(this.batchedConfirmationPart.onDidEmpty(() => {
			const batchedPart = this.batchedConfirmationPart;
			if (!batchedPart) {
				return;
			}

			const batchDomNode = batchedPart.domNode;
			const batchParent = batchDomNode.parentElement;
			if (batchParent) {
				batchParent.removeChild(batchDomNode);
			}

			batchedPart.dispose();
			this.batchedConfirmationPart = undefined;
			dom.show(this.domNode);
```', '`lastConfirmationToolPart` is cleared as soon as the first tool leaves `WaitingForConfirmation`, but that same tool part can continue owning an active batch (`part.hasActiveBatch`) while other tools remain pending. Clearing the reference early means later inserts won’t detect `batchDomNode` and can append tool wrappers after the batch, breaking the "batch stays at bottom" guarantee. Consider keeping a handle to the active batch (or the owning tool part) until the batch empties, e.g. clear only when the part has no active batch.', '## Pull request overview

This PR improves the chat tool-confirmation UX by batching multiple consecutive tool-call confirmations into a single, consolidated confirmation UI instead of rendering several separate confirmation widgets in a row.

**Changes:**
- Batch adjacent `WaitingForConfirmation` tool invocations into a single “batched confirmation” UI with per-item and bulk actions.
- Add a new `ChatBatchedToolConfirmationPart` renderer + styling, and wire batching into both the main chat list renderer and subagent tool grouping.
- Adjust related chat UI CSS (e.g. “see more” fade/positioning and some first-row request styling).

### Reviewed changes

Copilot reviewed 7 out of 7 changed files in this pull request and generated 3 comments.

