**src/vs/workbench/contrib/chat/browser/widget/chatContentParts/toolInvocationParts/chatBatchedToolConfirmationPart.ts:120**
* The MutationObserver setup here is likely never established for the initial batch: `ChatBatchedToolConfirmationPart` is constructed before its `domNode` is appended to a parent, so `parentElement` is null and `setupObserver` isn’t called. Since `addToolInvocation()` is also called from the constructor (before attachment), `moveToEndOfParent()` returns early and the observer still won’t be set, so the batch may not stay pinned to the bottom when later siblings are added. Consider deferring observer initialization until the node is attached (e.g. retry/schedule until `parentElement` exists, or accept/receive the parent element explicitly).
```
	private observeParentForReordering(): IDisposable {
		const parent = this.domNode.parentElement;
		if (parent) {
			this.setupObserver(parent);
		}
		// If not yet parented, moveToEndOfParent will set up the observer
		// when first called after the element is attached.
		return { dispose: () => this._parentObserver?.disconnect() };
	}
```
**src/vs/workbench/contrib/chat/browser/widget/chatContentParts/toolInvocationParts/chatBatchedToolConfirmationPart.ts:257**
* When the batch becomes empty you hide the DOM node and fire `onDidEmpty`, but the element stays in the DOM and the MutationObserver remains connected. Over time (multiple batches) this can leave hidden nodes/observers around unnecessarily. Consider removing the node from the DOM and/or disposing the part (disconnect observer, dispose stores) when `items.length === 0`, and let the owning `ChatToolInvocationPart` create a new batch part if needed later.
```
		if (this.items.length === 0) {
